5000|$|Well-established {{rules of}} {{evidence}} permit trial judges to exclude defense evidence if its probative value is outweighed by its unfair prejudice, confusion of the issues, or potential to mislead the jury. The Court noted that it had elaborated on this standard by permitting the exclusion of evidence that is [...] "repetitive, only marginally relevant or poses an <b>undue</b> risk of <b>harassment,</b> prejudice, or confusion of the issues." [...] Rules regulating the admissibility of third-party guilt apply this principle, because this evidence is often too speculative or remotely associated with the crime. The Court observed that these rules are widely accepted, and were not {{in and of themselves}} being challenged in this case.|$|R

